Complete Lesson

Vertical Slicing & Horizontal Decoupling: 5 Frontend Abstraction Layers - Driving the Registration Functionality

Last updated: March 3rd, 2024

Topics: Global state, State Management, React Context, Validation Logic, MVC, Networking, Error Handling, Validation, Caching

By this point, since implementing Horizontal Decoupling at the highest layer of the slice, we should now be dealing with a pretty thin implementation of the frontend. With only the layout & the components built out, we’re in good shape to drop down a layer of abstraction (into the Controller and the Model). These layers leave us to implement the registration/interaction, networking, error handling, validation & caching concerns.

Lesson goals

In this lesson, we’ll cover:

  • What the Transaction Script we’ll implement on the frontend should look like
  • The concerns we’ll have to cover to fill in the rest of the Controller and Model parts of MVC

Essential in Focus: Vertical Slicing (& Horizontal Decoupling)

So far I’ve been drawing your attention to Horizontal Decoupling a lot.

But it’s actually pretty important to call out Vertical Slicing here as well.

Here’s what’s important now.

If we consider our application’s abstraction layers to resemble a pie or a cake with layers..

Then the Vertical Slice — it represents not only the Width of the slice:

  • How much of the feature are we building?

But it also represents how deep we’ve currently gone in terms of implementing the feature.

  • How far along are we?

Vertical Slices are basically productivity tools, that — when appropriately chunked, enable us to focus on one thing at a time. I’m repeating myself here, but it’s important.

And within this slice we’re currently building out, we’re not done until everything within the slice exists — in our case, everything that will enable the sequence of UI interactions that represents your assignment requirements.

Briefly, as a reminder, thats:

main page → go to register page → register successfully → redirected back to front w/ the details, showing popularPosts w/ your username in the header

In terms of how deep we currently are, we’ve only made it to the View portion of MVC on the frontend — the Horizontal Abstraction Layers.

To finish up what’s left of this slice on the frontend, it’s time to build out the Controller (and whatever the ambiguous idea of the Model is on the frontend).

Note: I have my opinions on this, you’ll know them soon enough in Pattern-First.

The registration Transaction Script

If you’ve finished building out the View and all of the components, you would have finished building a RegistrationPage and even perhaps a RegistrationForm component like I’ve done here.

frontend/src/pages/RegistrationPage.tsx

import React from "react";
import { Layout } from "../components/layout";
import {
  RegistrationForm,
  RegistrationInput,
} from "../components/registrationForm";

export const RegisterPage = () => {

  const handleSubmitRegistrationForm = (input: RegistrationInput) => {
    // Logic goes here
  };

  return (
    <Layout>
      <div>Create Account</div>
      <RegistrationForm
        onSubmit={(input: RegistrationInput) =>
          handleSubmitRegistrationForm(input)
        }
      />
    </Layout>
  );
};

frontend/src/components/registrationForm.tsx

import React, { useState } from "react";
import { Link } from "react-router-dom";

export type RegistrationInput = {
  email: string;
  username: string;
  firstName: string;
  lastName: string;
}

interface RegistrationFormProps {
  onSubmit: (formDetails: RegistrationInput) => void;
}

export const RegistrationForm = (props: RegistrationFormProps) => {
  // Logic needs to go here

  return (
    <div className="registration-form">
      <div>Create Account</div>
      <input
        className="registration email"
        type="email"
        placeholder="email"
        onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
      ></input>
      <input
        className="registatation-input username"
        type="text"
        placeholder="username"
        onChange={(e) => setUsername(e.target.value)}
      ></input>
      <input
        className="registatation-input username"
        type="text"
        placeholder="first name"
        onChange={(e) => setFirstName(e.target.value)}
      ></input>
      <input
        className="registatation-input username"
        type="text"
        placeholder="last name"
        onChange={(e) => setLastName(e.target.value)}
      ></input>
      <div>
        <div className="to-login">
          <div>Already have an account?</div>
          <Link to="/login">Login</Link>
        </div>
        <button onClick={() => handleSubmit()} className="submit-button" type="submit">
          Submit
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

So what’s next?

Evidently, there’s a fair amount of work we need to do at various layers of abstraction.

But it all starts at the registration Transaction Script.

Here’s the pseudocode.

export const RegisterPage = () => {

  const handleSubmitRegistrationForm = (input: RegistrationInput) => {
    // Validate the form        // If the form is invalid      // Show an error toast (for invalid input)
    // If the form is valid, start isLoading    // Make the API call      // If the API call is successful        // Save the user details to the cache        // Stop the spinner        // Show the toast        // In 3 seconds, redirect to the main page           // If the call failed        // Stop the spinner        // Show the toast (for unknown error)
  };

  return (
    <Layout>
      <div>Create Account</div>
      <RegistrationForm
        onSubmit={(input: RegistrationInput) =>
          handleSubmitRegistrationForm(input)
        }
      />
    </Layout>
  );
};

I think you’ll agree that’s basically what we need to do in order to implement the majority of the requirements.

Let’s explore the abstraction layers we touch as we implement the success scenario.

1. Interaction (application logic) layer

The interaction (or application logic, as it’s more generally called) is basically the controller code.

The pseudocode we just looked at?

That’s fundamentally what that is.

Interaction logic, to me, is the layer of code that happens after a user invokes an interaction which could potentially perform a state change.

So when the user clicks submit, interaction logic (the controller code) runs the script and gets the bells & whistles spinning.

2. Validation logic layer

What do we need to validate?

The form, of course.

A simplistic, Transaction Script-like implementation of the validation logic we need could look like this:

type ValidationResult = {
  success: boolean;
  errorMessage?: string;
}

function validateForm (input: RegistrationInput): ValidationResult {
  if (input.email.indexOf('@') === -1) return { success: false, errorMessage: "Email invalid" };
  if (input.username.length < 2) return { success: false, errorMessage: "Username invalid" };
  return { success: true }
}

But I’ll leave it to you to think it through however you’d naturally like.

3. Networking logic layer

The networking logic layer is the layer that actually does the HTTP work.

Thank God for browser APIs and libraries.

We live in a day and age where we have access to tools like Axios and fetch, so there’s no need to implement this ourselves.

Although, a good practice is to wrap these abstractions in your own abstraction in order to create an api that makes it easier for us to work with.

For example, you could set it up like this:

import { RegistrationInput } from "./components/registrationForm";
import axios from 'axios'

export const api = {
  posts: {
    getPosts: () => {
      return axios.get('<http://localhost:3000/posts?sort=recent>')
    }
  },
  register: (input: RegistrationInput) => {
    return axios.post('<http://localhost:3000/users/new>', {
      ...input
    })
  }
}

In terms of Design Patterns, you could call this either a Facade, a Gateway or an Adapter.

4. Error handling logic

The simplest way to handle an error here is to wrap the entire script in a try-catch.

try {
  // Make API call
  // Save the user details to the cache
  // Stop the loading spinner
  // Show the toast
  // In 3 seconds, redirect to the main page
} catch (err) {
  // If the call failed
  // Stop the spinner
  // Show the toast (for unknown error)
}

5. Caching logic

Finally, the last important logic layer is caching.

I’ve chosen to use React Context to make things relatively simple and easy on myself, but in the past, I haven’t actually personally found scalable ways to use it. I actually find it to be a bit messy and I tend to prefer using tools like mobx instead.

Because we need global state, I’ll need to set up a Provider for the Users portion of the app.

Here’s what that’d look like.

frontend/src/contexts/usersContext.tsx

// UserContext.tsx
import React, { createContext, useState, useContext, ReactNode } from 'react';

// Define the shape of your user data
export interface UserData {
  username: string;
  // ... other relevant user data
}

// Create a context with initial data
const UserContext = createContext<{
  user: UserData | null;
  setUser: React.Dispatch<React.SetStateAction<UserData | null>>;
}>({
  user: null,
  setUser: () => null,
});

// Custom hook to access the user context
export const useUser = () => {
  return useContext(UserContext);
};

// Context provider component
export const UserProvider: React.FC<{children: ReactNode }> = ({ children }) => {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<UserData | null>(null);

  return (
    <UserContext.Provider value={{ user, setUser }}>
      {children}
    </UserContext.Provider>
  );
};

And then to use this, I’d need to wrap my the entire application tree

frontend/src/App.tsx

import "./App.css";
import "react-toastify/dist/ReactToastify.css";

import { BrowserRouter } from "react-router-dom";
import { Route, Routes } from "react-router-dom";
import { MainPage } from "./pages/mainPage";
import { RegisterPage } from "./pages/registerPage";
import { UserProvider } from "./contexts/userContext";
import { SpinnerProvider } from "./contexts/spinnerContext";

function App() {
  return (
    <SpinnerProvider>
      <UserProvider>
        <BrowserRouter>
          <meta name="color-scheme" content="light only"></meta>
          <Routes>
            <Route path="/" element={<MainPage />} />
            <Route path="/join" element={<RegisterPage />} />
          </Routes>
        </BrowserRouter>
      </UserProvider>
    </SpinnerProvider>
  );
}

export default App;

Summary

  • Horizontal decoupling is helping us implement the vertical slice in stages, chunking a bunch of concerns at a time
  • Implement the transaction script for registration involves writing code within the interaction/application, validation, networking, error handling & caching logic abstraction layers.
  • Ultimately, we’ve now covered all three parts of the MVC architectural pattern, but it is subject to debate just which concerns belong where.
  • By the end of this, you should have your registration transaction script working, able to create a new user, and you should get redirected to the main page with the user details saved in the header.
